title: Cupcake CNC Y-Axis Stepper Motor 40mm Fan Mount and Duct

description.text:
This is a combination fan mount and duct that mounts a 40mm fan to the back of the x/y carriage to blow air across the y-axis stepper motor under the carriage. This motor was getting hot on me during long prints and this thing solves that issue. I have uploaded .sldprt, .iges, and .stl files. I created this in Solidworks 2010.   
UPDATE Jan 9, 2013: I reworked the file such that it's Z-Up instead of skewed. It should have the fan mount flange down now.

Print this part out. Attach a 40mm fan to it. I had to use M3 x 25mm screws due to the thickness of my 40mm fan. My thinner 40mm fans could have used M3x16's. Remove the two rear M3x8 stepper mount screws from the rear of the carriage and screw in the shroud with M3 x 12 screws. I had to use three M3 washers under each screw head. An M3 x 10 screw would have been perfect. Wire the fan up to your closest 12V source and print away with the knowledge that your y-axis motor will not get hot.

comments.text: This was the first real thing I made for the cupcake I have now. The axis orientations are all messed up since I didn't output the STL with Z-up. I'll reupload it with Z-up so it will print right. I used RepG which let me rotate it completely around.

description.text:
This is a tiny little FPV quad I designed for a few parts I wanted to reuse. I wanted something that was a lot more durable than other options, but wasn't outrageously heavy, and this is it (I dont have a working scale, so I cant confirm the weight aspect, but it is very durable and flies very well). This quad can definitely take a beating, but isn't invincible. It is one of my first attempts at modelling and i'm pretty happy with the result! That said, I am totally open to any suggestions or requests anyone may have.

Some Notes/Heads up:

The standoffs (pictured blue) should fit snugly into place depending on how well tuned your printer is, but I would still recommend a dab of hot glue on all ends to hold them in place. I used too much in the photos.

Camera will require some sort of mounting component, I just used hot glue. (With my model it got out of hand quickly, you don't need that much glue)

I locked the motors in with some heat-shrink tubing, they fit tightly but the heat-shrink ensures they won't move in flight.

The feet haven't really been tested too thoroughly, I designed them to be disposable, and primarily to protect the motor wires under the arms. The feet slide along the arm, but don't fall off. They just snap onto the arm, and do their job.

My flight controller is held in place by foam tape, as is my VTX, and Rx (Above my FC)

Longer end of Standoff goes into lower plate.

Specs:

Made to house a Flight controller up to 34x34mm.

Designed to hold 8.5x20mm brushed motors (snugly)

Total Footprint= 71x112mm

Lower to Upper Plate= 16mm

Camera Mount to Upper Plate= about 14mm between closest edges

Top Plate= 64x40mm

As I said, I am open to any and all suggestions or requests, and will do my best to answer any questions you have. If you want to know anything about my build or the hobby itself, I will provide the info on my quad and hopefully answer your question.

NOTE: The completed quad above is an older version than the empty frame or the files supplied. I have since added a place for a rubber band to strap the battery in and other minor tweaks.

description.text:
I will be printing this in the near future to test it out, and make assembly instructions. However, most everything should be fairly accurate.   
This two cylinder oscillating steam engine was designed to be printed and then lost plastic cast. It is much closer to a real working engine than existing steam engines on thingiverse.

You will need 4 608 bearings. These are the standard skateboard bearings used on repraps. They're very cheap on ebay if you look hard enough. You will also need some 8mm or 5/16th shaft. Either metal, or wooden dowel, I used dowels because they're much easier to work with. You will also need some 3mm machine screws and nuts. You will also need something to put in the packing space, like an o-ring or string and grease. Print
1x top frame 1
1x top frame bearing cap
4x piston ring
and 2 of everything else. Print the pistons and piston rings with no brim, at 0.1mm layer height, and slowly. Print everything else however you like. Note that the top frame has bridges. The rods that connect the conrod to the piston should be exactly 2.05 inches long. Basically, make sure that theyre the right length so that the piston doesn't hit the ends of the cylinder.

description.text:
I am still in the process of printing and implementing these parts, but I thought I'd share the idea in the mean time.

*****NOTE: This requires modification of the A8's acrylic frame. The middle bottom cross member will need material removed to make way for the threaded rods.

*****ANOTHER NOTE: The location of the Y-axis motor and pulley mounting points for the Anet A8 should NOT be asymmetrical -- they just cut the holes off center. The belt is mounted the MIDDLE of the carriage, and centered between the smooth rods. Therefore, the belt needs to centered at the rear (motor), as well as the front (front pulley). As many A8 owners may have noticed, the belt is crooked as a dog's hind leg with the factory setup. While the issue at the rear can be solved by relocating the toothed pulley further down the motor shaft, I didn't like adding the extra leverage (aka stress) on the motor. MY PARTS RELOCATE THE MOTOR AND FRONT PULLEY to center, and inline with where the belt mounts to the carriage.

This is the beginning of my final solution to Y-axis stabilization for the A8. It's not so much a remix as it is a blenderization; a mashup of a few things and my handiwork. There are a few parts I've yet to add to the kit, but these will help stiffen things up for sure.

I liked matsekberg's idea of alleviating the Y-axis belt tension from the frame, but I wanted to utilize some braces to stiffen the printer up at the same time since the acrylic cross members are so flexible that they need reinforcing along their entire length. I wanted to have a fairly solid frame before eventually screwing it down to its own board. I plan to incorporate some aluminum channel/angle in my frame later, so I didn't print at 100% infill. I think one could use the same %s I did given how the parts are arranged, but I'm new to this, so....grain of salt.

Printer:

Anet A8

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.2

Infill:

varies per part

Notes:

I got a 3D printer kit for Christmas, and had never touched a CAD program before last week. This was my first project, so feedback on the design is more than welcome.

Rear Brace: I incorporated matsekberg's motor-mount component (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2045010) into a rear brace that I made. This brace spaces the 6mm threaded rods further apart (~31mm inside) to accommodate larger Y belt holders, and also has an integral Y-axis endstop mount. It is designed to integrate with my Motor Truss piece to prevent racking of the rear section of the frame (but the truss piece is not required to use the rear brace). I printed with 70% infill.

Motor Truss: I had planned to use Leo_N's Rear Frame Brace (thing:1852358) but, after printing, found the holes/slots for the threaded rod were off significantly (possibly due to an older printer design). Also, it was too tall to incorporate into the new design. Rather than cutting it down and modifying the holes (and seeing as I had just taken all the necessary measurements) I designed something to serve a similar purpose that "locks" into the rear brace as well. I printed ~30% infill.

Pulley Holder: This is a remixed version from the one in matsekberg's Y-axis Rework. I added some holes for M2 screws (~8mm, not including head) to retain the pulley screw, just because I was bored. It can be used as shown in matsekberg's setup. I printed with 100% infill.

Front Brace: I used Leo_N's front brace (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1857991), and mixed it with matsekberg's Y-axis Rework front component. From there I just changed the orientation of the holes, and located the four square acrylic frame reference lugs off of center to match the factory mistake. (Note: I forgot to add structure when slicing, and the only problem with the print was the bottoms of the square lugs were a little wonky. But nothing 10 seconds with a knife wouldn't fix. FYI)

While you've got things apart, take the time to turn your aluminum H-carriage so it is opposite what is shown in the assembly instructions. The single crossmember should on the bottom, while the two sides that attach to the sliders are on top. This will help get the belt level between the motor and pulley.

The hardware needed will be the same as matsekberg's Y-Axis Rework (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2045010), unless otherwise mentioned.

Assembly will also be very similar, with the removal of some acrylic adding an extra step.

Hello lightsaber fans!

Scarlet Impaler here to bring you an open source, free distribution 3D print file for a Chassis system designed to hold electronics for Saberforge Adaptive Saber Parts lightsabers.

How to read file names. For example "ASP_NEC_20mm_RCP" means.
ASP - hilt its made for
NEC - holds NEC boards
20mm - speaker size
RCP - refers to if includes a recharge port (if its left out, it doesn't have it)

Chassis lengths (speakers of either size only add a mm or two to total length):
ASP_CF-PC+CEX, RCP - 160mm
ASP_NEC_RCP - 166mm
ASP_NBv3_RCP - 138mm

This will cover how to install parts into this chassis. There are extensive tutorials and manuals for respective boards on how to wire everything.

You will need:
-18650 Holder and cell
-20mm speaker (rated for your card)
-Soundboard. Either NEC, NBv3, Crystal Focus/Petit Crouton and/or Color Extender
-Cheap recharge port (see picture)
-30 gauge wiring

Order of wiring up and install:
-Speaker
-Recharge port
-18650 holder (snip off pegs and leads)
-Everything else
-Soundboard

There is a channel that runs through the chassis along the bottom, its there for a nice and neat place to keep the wires tucked and out of the way. Hence why there is this specific order.

Print settings: I've printed this fine on a MonoPrice Maker Select (Wanhao i3 clone) with out problem. I think 30% infill is good, but if you plan on doing full contact dueling, it wouldn't hurt or take much more time or filament do set it at 100% infill. I printed with brim and supports. Your printer might be tuned in well enough to not need supports, but a brim will still be needed.

I do plan on doing a live stream of this on my FB page. https://www.facebook.com/thescarletimpaler, in the near future, and after that, a Youtube video of it.

Update Log:

-Got my hands on Railmasters 20mm and 23mm box speakers (both 9mm deep and 8w 8Ohm). They are just like a circle speaker, but attached to a box plate with 4 mounting holes in each corner. Will make versions for both of these and to use screws. I have gained a lot of faith in Railmasters' speakers over the past few months.

February 27, 2017!
-Took a few prints to get it right, but I successfully made the CF/PC + CEX variant. Will be uploaded tonight, with info on that.
-Currently test printing out variants without recharge ports. For if you put yours in the hilt or pommel, or you just don't need one because of the removable battery.
-Two versions of each soundboard are ready. One for 20mm and 28mm speaker each (note you still might need a bit of glue for the 28mm speaker.

-Then potentially final part of this project will be to figure out how to adapt Switchcraft Recharge Ports.

title: Dust Port Attachment for Bosch 1617 Plunge Base Router

description.text:
This dust collector port is for any vacuum port that has a ~1.25" nozzle on it. The neck is tapered to 1.25" about half way down, fits nice and snug. The hose pictured is the hose from the car cleaning kit for Rigid shop vacs. I wanted to make this as compact as possible, so I designed it for that size. I used (2) M4.7 x 12mm screws to attach it to the router. Hand knobs would be ideal here for quick install/removal, but I couldn't find any this small. Although, I don't see why you wouldn't just leave it on all the time.

I can only confirm that it works on Bosch 1617 model routers. If, by some odd random chance, someone can confirm it works on any other routers, please let me know. I'd be happy to hear from you.

It's a pretty simple print here on my Maker Select V2. The dust port is at a 45 degree angle, so no support is required. I printed this in PLA, but there should be no reason it wouldn't print in ABS as well. 195c/60c temps (PLA, of course). Nothing too fancy.

Why? What are these for?

The pins that go through the rollers in this were a little too thick and wouldn't fit, so I pulled them into blender 3-D, and made them a bit narrower (95% scaling on the female pins and 85% scaling on the male pins, so that they would fit into the female pins). I constrained the scaling to just the X and Y axes, so that they remained the same length, in order to fit properly with the rest of the mechanism. A drop of superglue on each pin helped set them in place.

There is also a tiny part named "splint" in the model, which is a little locking pin for the two parts of the handle. This also was too wide to fit the hole, but I did not scale a new version, as the fit of the two larger handle pieces was so tight that a locking pin was not needed. (Nor was any glue!)

title: Prusa I3 MK2 Raspberry Pi Camera Mount

description.text:
I wanted to lift my Raspberry Pi camera up a little above bed level on my Prusa I3 MK2 to get a better view of the print for timelapse videos. So I started with the ball mount from Exclusive and tweaked it to come straight off the corner of the bed, in line with the x-frame underneath, and put fingers on the end.

Then I used the camera case back and two of the 40mm link arms from here: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:247590

and the camera case front from here: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:403712

All assembled with a couple of m3x16 screws and m3 nuts. This got the camera up above the bed a bit to give a better vantage point of the whole print. I attached the mounting arm under the x-frame in the front right corner, replacing the existing m8 screw with a new m10 screw to account for the thickness of the mounting arm. Just make sure to set it all back far enough that it doesn't get hit by the hot end at its closest, and doesn't interfere with the y axis rods below.

Take a look at my uploaded pictures to see how this is assembled, and even a picture of the bed taken from this mount so you can see what can be captured from the Raspberry Pi Camera (v2).

description.text:
This simple little stand organizes your Flip Flops (Jandals / Thongs / Sandals) to keep them tidy and save space by making them stand upright. Once mounted the stand can also be hung up on a hook if required and the Flip Flops will stay secure and held in place... no more messy Flip Flops lying around or taking up more floor space than is necessary.

The stand is easy to use... just slide your Flip Flops into the slots heel down with the soles facing each other. This puts a small amount of pressure between them so they stand upright and stay in place in the stand.

Five versions are provided for different thickness heels ranging from 15mm to 35mm. This should cover most thickness of Flip Flops. Determining the size to print is easy... just measure the thickness of the heel of your Flip Flops and print the size required.

For example:

With a heel thickness of 20mm use the 20mm file and you should have a snug / slight compression when the Flip Flops are inserted into the slots. There will also be tension between the soles that holds the Flip Flops in and secure.

With a heel thickness of 22mm go up to the 25mm file. The heels will be slightly loose in the slots but there will be tension between the soles so the Flip Flops will still be securely held in the stand.

This is an easy-to-use practical and space-saving solution. Print in your colour of choice and color code for different people or pair of Flip Flops so they know the correct stand for the pair concerned. Handy to use yourself but also great as a small gift.

The stands are all quite small so don't take long to print or use much filament. Please post images of your stands in use for others to see.

Please refer to the print settings / instructions and the images for additional information.
